    "205415116": {
      "title": "Pivotal role of dermal IL-17-producing оҒ§оҒӨ T cells in skin inflammation",
      "abstract": "Summary Interleukin-23 (IL-23) and CD4 + T helper 17 (Th17) cells are thought to be critical in psoriasis pathogenesis. Here, we report that IL-23 predominantly stimulated dermal ОіОҙ T cells to produce IL-17 that led to disease progression. Dermal ОіОҙ T cells constitutively expressed the IL-23 receptor (IL-23R) and transcriptional factor RORОіt. IL-17 production from dermal ОіОҙ T cells was independent of ОұОІ T cells. The epidermal hyperplasia and inflammation induced by IL-23 were significantly decreased in T cell receptor Оҙ-deficient ( Tcrd вҲ’/вҲ’ ) and IL-17 receptor-deficient ( Il17ra вҲ’/вҲ’ ) mice but occurred normally in Tcra вҲ’/вҲ’ mice. Imiquimod-induced skin pathology was also significantly decreased in Tcrd вҲ’/вҲ’ mice. Perhaps further promoting disease progression, IL-23 stimulated dermal ОіОҙ T cell expansion. In psoriasis patients, ОіОҙ T cells were greatly increased in affected skin and produced large amounts of IL-17. Thus, IL-23-responsive dermal ОіОҙ T cells are the major IL-17 producers in the skin and may represent a novel target for the treatment of psoriasis."
